06772nam a22008175i 9780520976467DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1248759907  a97805209764677 a10.1525/97805209764672doi  a(DE-B1597)577526  a(OCoLC)1221014361  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aKF372b.K39 2021 7aHIS0580002bisacsh04a340.092/5209732231 aKay, Herma Hill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaving the Way :bThe First American Women Law Professors /cHerma Hill Kay. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw in the Public Square ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Leading the Way -- t2 Armstrong’s Pre-World War II Contemporaries -- t3 The Czarina of Legal Education -- t4 From the Library to the Faculty: Five Women Who Changed Careers -- t5 The Mid-Fifties -- t6 The End of an Era -- t7 The Next Decades Ruth Bader Ginsburg and women law professors from the 1960s to the 1980s -- tConclusion -- tAppendix a note on Clemence Myers Smith, the sixth woman law professor -- tAfterword -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first wave of trailblazing female law professors and the stage they set for American democracy. When it comes to breaking down barriers for women in the workplace, Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s name speaks volumes for itself—but, as she clarifies in the foreword to this long-awaited book, there are too many trailblazing names we do not know. Herma Hill Kay, former Dean of UC Berkeley School of Law and Ginsburg’s closest professional colleague, wrote Paving the Way to tell the stories of the first fourteen female law professors at ABA- and AALS-accredited law schools in the United States. Kay, who became the fifteenth such professor, labored over the stories of these women in order to provide an essential history of their path for the more than 2,000 women working as law professors today and all of their feminist colleagues. Because Herma Hill Kay, who died in 2017, was able to obtain so much first-hand information about the fourteen women who preceded her, Paving the Way is filled with details, quiet and loud, of each of their lives and careers from their own perspectives. Kay wraps each story in rich historical context, lest we forget the extraordinarily difficult times in which these women lived. Paving the Way is not just a collection of individual stories of remarkable women but also a well-crafted interweaving of law and society during a historical period when women’s voices were often not heard and sometimes actively muted. The final chapter connects these first fourteen women to the “second wave” of women law professors who achieved tenure-track appointments in the 1960s and 1970s, carrying on the torch and analogous challenges. This is a decidedly feminist project, one that Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg advocated for tirelessly and admired publicly in the years before her death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen law teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aAmsler, Margaret Harris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Barbara Nachtrieb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCain, Patricia A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaggett, Harriet Spiller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Justice Ruth Bader, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrauskopf, Joan Miday, econtributor.4ctb4h